This paper is about learning disentangled representations, which is a problem in representation learning and machine learning in general. The paper focuses on the impact of limited supervision on state-of-the-art disentanglement methods, which is a topic that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. Specifically, the paper discusses the use of manual labeling of training examples, which is a common technique in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also discusses the use of unsupervised learning methods, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper performs a large-scale study, which involves training over 29000 models, which is a topic in neural networks (cs.NE).
